\title{Lawvereâ€™s fixed point theorem}
\date{2024-01-31}
\author{jonmsterling}
\contributor{marcelofiore}
\taxon{theorem}
\import{jms-00JB}

\p{Given sets #{A} and #{X}, if there exists a [surjection](jms-00M8) #{A\twoheadrightarrow\prn{A\to X}} then every function #{X\to X} has a [fixed point](jms-00NG); and hence #{X} is a singleton.}

\proof{
 \p{Let #{e\colon A\twoheadrightarrow\prn{A\to X}} be a [surjection](jms-00M8).
 Let #{f\colon X\to X} be a function of which are trying to find a [fixed point](jms-00NG). Let #{h\colon A\to X} be the following function:}

 ##{
  h\prn{a} = f\prn{e\prn{a}\prn{a}}
 }

 \p{Because #{e\colon A\twoheadrightarrow\prn{A\to X}} is a [surjection](jms-00M8), we may find #{a_h\in A} such that #{e\prn{a_h} = h}. Therefore, we have #{e\prn{a_h}\prn{a_h} = f\prn{e\prn{a_h}\prn{a_h}}} and so #{e\prn{a_h}\prn{a_h}} is a [fixed point](jms-00NG) of #{f}.}

 \p{Finally, we conclude that #{X} is a singleton: first of all #{X} has at least one element (the fixed point of the identity function). Now, let #{x_0\not= x_1\in X} be two unequal elements of #{X} and let #{f\colon X\to X} be the function that sends #{x_0} to #{x_1} and everything else to #{x_0}. By assumption, we have a fixed point #{p\in X} of #{f}. We now proceed by cases:}
 \ol{
  \li{If #{p=x_0}, then we have #{f\prn{p}=x_1} and #{f\prn{p}=p} and thus #{x_0=x_1}, a contradiction.}
  \li{If #{p\not= x_0}, then we have #{f\prn{p}=x_0} and #{f\prn{p}=p}, also a contradiction.}
 }
}